Overview

[Num 19:1](../../../bib/kjv/num019.htm#001.md), The water of separation
made of the ashes of a red heifer; [Num
19:11](../../../bib/kjv/num019.htm#011.md), The law for the use of it in
purification of the unclean.

[Numbers 19:2](../../../bib/kjv/num019.htm#002.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_002">num 19:2</span></span>

the ordinance: [Num 31:21](../../../bib/kjv/num031.htm#021.md); [Heb
9:10](../../../bib/kjv/heb009.htm#010.md)

a red heifer: The following curious particulars have been remarked in
this ordinance:

1\. A heifer was appointed for sacrifice, in opposition to the Egyptian
superstition, which held these sacred, and worshipped their goddess Isis
under this form; and this appears the more likely, because males only
were chosen for sacrifice. So Herodotus says, they sacrifice males, both
old and young; but it is not lawful for them to offer females.

2\. It was to be a red heifer, because the Egyptians sacrificed red
bulls to the evil demon Typhon.

3\. It was to be without spot, having no mixture of any other colour.
Plutarch says, the Egyptians "sacrifice red bulls, and select them with
such scrupulous attention, that if the animal has a single black or
white hair, they reckon it αθυτον, unfit to be sacrificed."

4\. Without blemish. (See note on [Lev
22:21](../../../bib/kjv/lev022.htm#021)..md)

5\. On which never came yoke. because an animal which had been used for
a common purpose was deemed improper for sacrifice. [Num
